Basic Statistics

##a.Sibling survey
sbl = c(2,3,0,5,2,1,1,0,3,3)

summary(sbl)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0       1       2       2       3       5
##Mode Calculation

names(sort(-table(sbl)))[1]
## [1] "3"
##Variance
var(sbl)
## [1] 2.444444
##Standard deviation
sd(sbl)
## [1] 1.563472
##b.Ageing Survey

age = c(23, 25, 18, 45, 30, 21, 22, 19, 29, 35)

##i. Covariance between siblings and ages
cov(sbl, age)
## [1] 11.88889
## Correlation between siblings and ages
cor(sbl, age)
## [1] 0.9116971
##Positive or negative correlation between siblings and student ages
plot(sbl, age, xlab="Nro of Siblings", ylab="Age")

##There is strong positive correlation betwen siblings and student age

## [1] "we see that the rows are neighbourhoods of the Boston area wich are the elements and the\ncolumns are 14 predictor variables, including:\ncrim: per capita crime rate by town\nzn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft\nindus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town\nchas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)\nnox: nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)\nrm: average number of rooms per dwelling\nage: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940\ndis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres\nrad: index of accessibility to radial highways\ntax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000\nptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town\nblack: 1000(Bk - 0.63)ˆ2, where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town\nlstat: lower status of the population (percent)\nmedv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s"
